WEBVTT

00:02.040 --> 00:04.750
♪ Back in the days
when I was young ♪
 Dre: Growing up,
 we didn't have many choices.

00:04.750 --> 00:06.170
If you were bored,
 you went outside and played

00:06.170 --> 00:08.880
with water gun or ball.

00:08.880 --> 00:11.040
If you were hungry,
 it was Mickey D's

00:11.040 --> 00:13.080
or, in my case, McRuby.

00:13.080 --> 00:15.420
And it wasn't just food
 and toys.

00:15.420 --> 00:17.920
It was our choices of what
 we could actually be in life.

00:19.750 --> 00:21.170
See, limited choices

00:21.170 --> 00:23.460
limited what we could imagine
 for ourselves

00:23.460 --> 00:26.250
and, thusly,
 what we would become.

00:26.250 --> 00:28.460
But nowadays,
 things are different.

00:28.460 --> 00:31.460
Children have tons
 of choices about everything --

00:31.460 --> 00:33.210
water guns,

00:33.210 --> 00:34.500
burgers,

00:34.500 --> 00:36.420
even role models.

00:36.420 --> 00:38.830
And each choice they make
 is an opportunity

00:38.830 --> 00:40.830
to help them form
 their identity --

00:40.830 --> 00:43.250
tell the world who they are.

00:43.250 --> 00:46.210
But what happens when the world
 makes a choice for them

00:46.210 --> 00:48.580
that goes directly
 against that identity?

00:48.580 --> 00:49.880
Diane: Thank you, Janine.

00:49.880 --> 00:52.540
Rainbow:
Yes, thank you, Janine!

00:52.540 --> 00:54.250
This white doll
is beautiful!

00:54.250 --> 00:56.500
[ Laughs ]

00:56.500 --> 00:57.620
Do you still have
the receipt?

00:57.620 --> 00:59.920
♪♪

01:04.959 --> 01:06.290
The receipt?

01:06.290 --> 01:07.790
Why? Why? Is there --
Is there something wrong?

01:07.790 --> 01:09.460
This is
a GirlStory doll.

01:09.460 --> 01:11.120
Yeah.
 It's celebrating women
throughout history.

01:11.120 --> 01:14.710
Yeah.
 This one is
Winnie the Wartime Doctor.

01:14.710 --> 01:16.330
Oh, yeah.
 She's like you, Bow,
except a real doctor.

01:16.330 --> 01:19.920
Okay, um, Janine,
I'm a real doctor.

01:19.920 --> 01:21.330
Dre: Mm-hmm.
 And that is a doll.

01:21.330 --> 01:22.620
You're a doll!
[ Laughs ]

01:22.620 --> 01:23.920
It's -- It's --
It's a lovely doll.

01:23.920 --> 01:25.710
But, you know,
we're just dealing

01:25.710 --> 01:27.040
with numbers here,
Janine.
 Uh-huh.

01:27.040 --> 01:28.330
We have enough
white dolls.

01:28.330 --> 01:30.330
You know, the black/white ratio
is just --

01:30.330 --> 01:31.880
just a little off.
 Yeah.

01:31.880 --> 01:34.080
You have a black/white ratio
for dolls?

01:34.080 --> 01:35.330
With everything, Janine.

01:35.330 --> 01:37.250
Literally
with everything.
 Yeah.

01:37.250 --> 01:38.670
You know,
I'm constantly aware

01:38.670 --> 01:40.920
of how many black people
are in a restaurant,

01:40.920 --> 01:42.960
how many black characters
are in a movie...

01:42.960 --> 01:45.170
Yeah.
 ...and it also affects
the way that we buy cereal.

01:45.170 --> 01:47.210
Nobody really eats
the Count Chocula, but...

01:47.210 --> 01:49.000
Yeah,
but I still buy it.

01:49.000 --> 01:50.620
Yeah.

01:50.620 --> 01:53.250
I-Is Count Chocula
even black?

01:53.250 --> 01:56.120
Janine, his last name
is Chocula.

01:56.120 --> 02:00.210
♪♪

02:00.210 --> 02:04.000
I gathered you kids here
to announce that, sadly,

02:04.000 --> 02:06.420
my Spades partner,
Earnest Woodbine,

02:06.420 --> 02:08.380
passed on today.
 Oh.
 Diane: Aw.

02:08.380 --> 02:11.210
And now
I need a new partner.

02:11.210 --> 02:13.330
Didn't you say
he died today?

02:13.330 --> 02:15.790
Don't you judge the way I mourn,
little boy.

02:15.790 --> 02:18.380
Winning was very important
to Earnest and me.

02:18.380 --> 02:19.790
Why don't you just partner
with somebody

02:19.790 --> 02:21.710
that's already
in your Spades group?

02:21.710 --> 02:23.960
For some reason,
they're put off by me.

02:23.960 --> 02:26.750
This is my house [bleep]

02:26.750 --> 02:28.960
[ Laughs ]

02:28.960 --> 02:30.790
Haters, all of 'em.

02:30.790 --> 02:33.290
But that just means that now
there's an opportunity

02:33.290 --> 02:36.380
for one of you
to become my new partner.

02:36.380 --> 02:37.920
"Opportunity" feels strong.

02:37.920 --> 02:39.540
Diane, you're out.

02:39.540 --> 02:41.250
You're smart and mean,

02:41.250 --> 02:43.620
but your mole-like vision
concerns me.

02:43.620 --> 02:45.040
Well, okay.
 Yeah.

02:45.040 --> 02:46.330
Jack, you're out.

02:46.330 --> 02:47.250
You know why.

02:47.250 --> 02:48.330
Yeah, I do.

02:48.330 --> 02:49.750
Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.

02:49.750 --> 02:51.040
Zoey...
 I don't care.

02:51.040 --> 02:53.120
Sure, you don't.
Mm-hmm.

02:53.120 --> 02:55.620
And...Junior!

02:55.620 --> 02:57.000
I know.

02:57.000 --> 02:59.500
My ears are too big,
and I tend to ramble,

02:59.500 --> 03:01.580
and people think
my mustache is dirt.

03:01.580 --> 03:05.080
♪♪

03:06.960 --> 03:10.920
Unh-unh-unh. See, it is that
laser beam of self-reflection

03:10.920 --> 03:13.500
that makes you
the perfect partner.

03:13.500 --> 03:15.920
You are the key
to me beating Doris.

03:15.920 --> 03:17.290
Who's Doris?

03:17.290 --> 03:20.750
She's the Cobra Kai
to my Daniel-san.

03:20.750 --> 03:24.290
And I swear on Earnest's
clogged-up dead heart

03:24.290 --> 03:26.790
that that witch
will not take our title!

03:26.790 --> 03:28.330
Hey, hey!
Where y'all going?

03:28.330 --> 03:31.920
Unh-unh. You losers are
our new practice partners.

03:31.920 --> 03:32.750
Get in here!

03:32.750 --> 03:35.210
♪♪

03:35.210 --> 03:36.380
Good news, guys!

03:36.380 --> 03:38.880
The Boxable people
loved your pitch.

03:38.880 --> 03:42.170
Yes. I knew they would,
'cause it's so simple.

03:42.170 --> 03:43.620
"Boxable -- Come on."

03:43.620 --> 03:44.790
Not yours, Josh.

03:44.790 --> 03:47.080
They hated it,
and they hated you.

03:47.080 --> 03:48.880
They said you reeked
of desperation.

03:48.880 --> 03:51.250
Aw.
Boxable? Come on.

03:51.250 --> 03:54.330
But, Dre,
yours was a slam dunk.

03:54.330 --> 03:57.000
The artwork was beautiful,
casting was perfect,

03:57.000 --> 03:59.290
but it was your tag line
that gave us the chills.

03:59.290 --> 04:02.040
"Boxable --
The gold standard in shipping."

04:02.040 --> 04:03.580
Good call
on the gold, Dre.

04:03.580 --> 04:06.080
Pewter was not
the way to go.

04:06.080 --> 04:07.620
Every day I learn
from you.

04:07.620 --> 04:09.500
Man, no time for modesty,
all right?

04:09.500 --> 04:11.580
I killed it.
 So good.

04:11.580 --> 04:13.460
You're off probation, Dre.

04:13.460 --> 04:14.710
I've been on probation?

04:14.710 --> 04:16.209
Only since I hired you.

04:16.209 --> 04:19.670
♪♪

04:19.670 --> 04:22.250
If we have to return Winnie,
why don't we get something

04:22.250 --> 04:26.000
that I actually want,
like a sword or a bear trap?

04:26.000 --> 04:28.290
Or a doll
that you can relate to.

04:28.290 --> 04:29.790
Hello.
 Hi.

04:29.790 --> 04:31.290
We'd like
to make an exchange.

04:31.290 --> 04:32.500
Oh.
Ooh, Winnie.

04:32.500 --> 04:33.920
Well,
that's a surprise!

04:33.920 --> 04:36.290
She's our best-selling
GirlStory doll.

04:36.290 --> 04:38.080
She invented
the tourniquet.

04:38.080 --> 04:39.580
Oh, wow!
 Oh.
 But you know what?
No worries.

04:39.580 --> 04:42.670
We have tons of other dolls
for you to choose from.
 Oh!

04:42.670 --> 04:44.420
Like right here,
we have Cassandra.

04:44.420 --> 04:45.710
She's a pioneer woman.

04:45.710 --> 04:47.790
Uh, we're actually looking
for a doll

04:47.790 --> 04:50.460
that's, um, you know,
err, like...

04:50.460 --> 04:51.750
Has hands?
 N-- Oh.

04:51.750 --> 04:52.670
Oh, all our dolls
have hands.

04:52.670 --> 04:54.500
Well, mm,
except for a few

04:54.500 --> 04:56.620
of our
differently abled dolls.

04:56.620 --> 04:58.210
Uh-huh.
Oh, look at that.

04:58.210 --> 05:00.080
Oh, and this is Polio Patty --
love her.

05:00.080 --> 05:01.670
Got to be careful
when you move her, but...

05:01.670 --> 05:03.210
Okay, well, we could dance
around this forever,

05:03.210 --> 05:04.880
uh...Patrice.

05:04.880 --> 05:06.210
Oh, it's pronounced
"Pat-riss."

05:06.210 --> 05:07.670
"Pat-riss."
 Rhymes with mattress?

05:07.670 --> 05:10.500
Oh.
 G-- Oh, that's -- Okay.

05:10.500 --> 05:11.420
Um...

05:11.420 --> 05:13.830
where are your
black dolls?

05:13.830 --> 05:16.540
[ Chuckles ] Okay,
why didn't you just say so?

05:16.540 --> 05:17.710
Well, kind of thought
I'd just see 'em.

05:17.710 --> 05:19.250
I got you, girl!

05:19.250 --> 05:20.380
Okay.
 Come on, ladies. Follow me.

05:20.380 --> 05:21.540
We're taking a hike.

05:21.540 --> 05:23.000
Oh.
 Oh, so they're, like...

05:23.000 --> 05:24.380
separate area.

05:24.380 --> 05:27.830
Ladies, allow me to introduce
you to Sassy Sadie

05:27.830 --> 05:29.330
and equally Sassy Selma.

05:29.330 --> 05:32.040
Uh-huh, okay.

05:32.040 --> 05:33.250
So, let's see here.

05:33.250 --> 05:35.540
Sassy Sadie --
"Little Sadie Crawford

05:35.540 --> 05:37.670
left home with nothing
but the clothes on her back

05:37.670 --> 05:39.580
and a desire to be free."

05:39.580 --> 05:41.790
So, she's a slave?
 Not anymore.

05:41.790 --> 05:44.540
She escaped and eventually
learned to read...sort of.

05:44.540 --> 05:45.960
So, she's
a runaway slave.

05:45.960 --> 05:47.330
Who can read.

05:47.330 --> 05:48.960
Okay,
so [clears throat]

05:48.960 --> 05:50.460
you have dozens
of disabled...

05:50.460 --> 05:51.620
Ooh,
differently abled.

05:51.620 --> 05:56.000
Fine, differently-abled,
and hundreds

05:56.000 --> 05:58.250
of amazingly successful
white dolls,

05:58.250 --> 06:00.540
but only two black dolls.

06:00.540 --> 06:02.580
African-American.
 Uh-huh.

06:02.580 --> 06:04.420
Let's see what the other one is,
shall we?

06:04.420 --> 06:06.880
Mm. Selma --
the Civil Rights leader

06:06.880 --> 06:08.540
who marched on Selma.

06:08.540 --> 06:10.460
And that doesn't
feel lazy to you?

06:10.460 --> 06:11.920
Well, she's also
a mother of 11.

06:11.920 --> 06:14.000
11, seriously?

06:14.000 --> 06:15.290
So, you think
we just keep having kids,

06:15.290 --> 06:16.500
just kids on kids on kids?

06:16.500 --> 06:18.880
Easy, Mom.
You're on your fifth.

06:18.880 --> 06:21.040
[ Clears throat ]
 Okay, well, these are basically
the same doll,

06:21.040 --> 06:22.080
just wearing
different clothes!

06:22.080 --> 06:23.250
Oh, that's not true.

06:23.250 --> 06:24.420
Yet they both
have lanterns!

06:24.420 --> 06:25.750
But for
different reasons.

06:25.750 --> 06:27.170
Oh, come on.

06:27.170 --> 06:29.040
This is unbelievable!

06:29.040 --> 06:30.920
You know what sounds
unbelievable right now?

06:30.920 --> 06:34.000
A nice cold
Orange Julius.

06:34.000 --> 06:35.960
Okay, no, I'm not done.
I'm not done, sweetheart.

06:35.960 --> 06:37.330
I am just a little girl,

06:37.330 --> 06:39.170
and it would be embarrassing
for both of us

06:39.170 --> 06:41.210
if I had to drag you out.

06:41.210 --> 06:44.830
Well, let me tell you I have not
even begun to be embarrassing.

06:44.830 --> 06:48.170
In the words of the great
Maya Ang--

06:48.170 --> 06:50.250
Hey! Oh, you are strong!
I will be back! Ow!

06:54.080 --> 06:54.920
Hey.
How was your day?

06:54.920 --> 06:56.880
I, um...

06:56.880 --> 06:59.880
went a little bit crazy
at GirlStory.

06:59.880 --> 07:03.250
She recited Maya Angelou's
"Phenomenal Woman"

07:03.250 --> 07:04.790
all the way out
to Sunglass Hut.

07:04.790 --> 07:07.170
In her Maya Angelou
voice?
 You know it.

07:07.170 --> 07:12.000
That store only has
two black dolls -- two.

07:12.000 --> 07:13.500
And they're not doctors.

07:13.500 --> 07:16.290
One's a slave,
and one's a Selma.

07:16.290 --> 07:18.380
Selma!
I'm outraged!

07:18.380 --> 07:20.580
You know, you look so cute
when you're outraged.

07:20.580 --> 07:21.920
Oh, come on.

07:21.920 --> 07:24.830
That is the one thing
that reminds me

07:24.830 --> 07:25.920
that you're black --

07:25.920 --> 07:28.040
this, and when you
send your food back.

07:28.040 --> 07:31.710
I'm sorry to complain,
but I wasn't expecting garbage.

07:33.750 --> 07:36.290
That's how we made
this baby.

07:36.290 --> 07:37.960
Seriously,
this is not funny.

07:37.960 --> 07:39.620
Well...
 This is a big deal.

07:39.620 --> 07:42.580
The images that we see
affect who we are...

07:42.580 --> 07:44.620
Mm-hmm.
 ...and who we aspire
to become.

07:44.620 --> 07:46.500
I mean, it's bad enough
we didn't have role models

07:46.500 --> 07:48.040
growing up,
but we made it past that.

07:48.040 --> 07:49.500
We made it through.

07:49.500 --> 07:51.420
But we have role models now,
Dre...
 Mm-hmm.

07:51.420 --> 07:53.710
...doctors, lawyers,
movie stars.

07:53.710 --> 07:55.500
Our kids seeing themselves
reflected

07:55.500 --> 07:57.170
in our culture
is important.

07:57.170 --> 07:59.210
Yes, I know this,
Bow.

07:59.210 --> 08:02.250
Do you think I need to see
Viola Davis snot-cry

08:02.250 --> 08:04.040
every episode of
"How To Get Away With Murder"?

08:04.040 --> 08:05.790
I don't,
but the kids do,

08:05.790 --> 08:07.880
to see that they can be
whatever it is they want to be.

08:07.880 --> 08:11.120
Right.
 Except now,
Jack wants to be an actor.

08:11.120 --> 08:13.750
You're innocent!
I know it!

08:15.290 --> 08:17.500
Whatever, Dre.
Images matter.

08:17.500 --> 08:20.380
That's why your job
is so important,

08:20.380 --> 08:21.880
and I do not say that
enough.

08:21.880 --> 08:23.040
No, you don't.

08:23.040 --> 08:24.710
You normally
say the opposite,

08:24.710 --> 08:26.500
and it's normally
followed up with,

08:26.500 --> 08:27.960
"You know, I save lives.

08:27.960 --> 08:31.120
And you, Dre, you promote
empty consumerism."

08:31.120 --> 08:34.039
Well, not today.
Dre, I'm proud of you.

08:34.039 --> 08:37.620
You effect change
in a real and tangible way.

08:37.620 --> 08:40.419
Yes.
I do do that, don't I?

08:40.419 --> 08:41.960
Don't get ahead
of yourself.
 I --

08:41.960 --> 08:42.880
I save lives.

08:42.880 --> 08:44.420
You make ads.

08:44.420 --> 08:46.460
I'm a doctor.

08:48.000 --> 08:49.960
[ Laughter ]
 Unbelievable.

08:49.960 --> 08:51.710
Hey, Dre, good news.
 Hmm?

08:51.710 --> 08:55.040
Boxable wants to fast-track
your campaign for this summer!

08:55.040 --> 08:56.750
Great.
We're not doing it.

08:56.750 --> 08:58.040
It's garbage.
 What?

08:58.040 --> 09:00.710
I can't do the spot
with an all-white family.

09:00.710 --> 09:03.290
Oh, my God.
 Buckle up, everyone.

09:03.290 --> 09:05.250
Time to board
the S.S. GuiltTrip.

09:05.250 --> 09:07.080
I feel like this is
gonna be about Katrina.

09:07.080 --> 09:09.670
No, but that is a story
that needs to be told.

09:09.670 --> 09:11.460
No, uh, well, maybe.

09:11.460 --> 09:14.420
Boxable is looking
for the gold standard.

09:14.420 --> 09:16.710
Who's to say
that black people

09:16.710 --> 09:18.960
can't be
the gold standard?

09:18.960 --> 09:20.540
Dre's right.

09:20.540 --> 09:22.380
What make you think we don't
wanna open up a box of presents

09:22.380 --> 09:24.250
and laugh about
how good life is?

09:24.250 --> 09:27.120
[ Laughs ] Oh, life.

09:27.120 --> 09:29.750
This is my snifter,
'cause I like to drink cognac

09:29.750 --> 09:31.790
when I open boxes
and make valid points.

09:31.790 --> 09:34.120
[ Sighs ]
 Stevens:
Okay, Dre, the gold standard --

09:34.120 --> 09:36.460
it suggests success,
dependability,

09:36.460 --> 09:38.330
shirts tucked into pants.

09:38.330 --> 09:40.210
Dre,
it's just one commercial.

09:40.210 --> 09:42.830
It's not
just one commercial.

09:42.830 --> 09:46.080
In the beginning,
it was almost every commercial.

09:46.080 --> 09:47.920
A-And things --
they got better,

09:47.920 --> 09:50.960
but we can't assume
that progress is permanent.

09:50.960 --> 09:53.710
White is the default,

09:53.710 --> 09:56.960
unless someone chooses
to move the ball forward.

09:56.960 --> 09:59.120
Please don't let him say
that he is the one to
move the ball forward.

09:59.120 --> 10:02.210
And I am the one
to move the ball forward.

10:02.210 --> 10:04.830
Damn it, Dre!
Now you're back on probation!

10:04.830 --> 10:06.080
You know what?

10:06.080 --> 10:08.710
I am gonna recast this ad

10:08.710 --> 10:12.460
and give the world
a different "gold" standard.

10:12.460 --> 10:15.000
No, no, no!
The client loves what we have!

10:15.000 --> 10:17.830
Yeah, white people
love white people.

10:17.830 --> 10:20.290
And vegetables.

10:21.420 --> 10:23.250
Oh!

10:23.250 --> 10:25.790
I was hoping
you would be off today.

10:25.790 --> 10:27.830
Oh, we don't get days off,
or benefits.

10:27.830 --> 10:28.710
How can I help you today?

10:28.710 --> 10:31.880
Okay, um, I love

10:31.880 --> 10:35.000
that you're teaching young women
about their history.

10:35.000 --> 10:36.830
Guilty.
 [ Laughs ]

10:36.830 --> 10:38.040
What I don't love...
 Uh-oh.

10:38.040 --> 10:41.210
...is that with all
 the black history,

10:41.210 --> 10:47.040
that you choose to focus on
our oppression and struggle

10:47.040 --> 10:50.830
when there are so many
role models to choose from --

10:50.830 --> 10:52.040
Josephine Baker,

10:52.040 --> 10:54.210
Dorothy Dandridge,
Shonda Rhimes,

10:54.210 --> 10:56.500
Misty Copeland,
Michelle Obama.

10:56.500 --> 10:57.830
Ooh, I know her.

10:57.830 --> 10:59.790
And you know what?
These are amazing suggestions,

10:59.790 --> 11:01.880
and at GirlStory,
we take customer feedback

11:01.880 --> 11:03.250
very seriously.

11:03.250 --> 11:05.210
Okay, so...
 I would just love it

11:05.210 --> 11:07.540
if you could just write
those down here in this book,

11:07.540 --> 11:10.670
and I will personally make sure
that your concerns are heard.

11:10.670 --> 11:12.170
Great. I'm gonna write it down
in the book.
 Thank you.

11:14.420 --> 11:16.540
Hey, wait a minute.

11:16.540 --> 11:18.380
Are you telling me
that my complaint

11:18.380 --> 11:21.580
about a lack of diversity
is actually gonna go below

11:21.580 --> 11:24.380
"Not enough icing on the
cinnamon rolls in the café"?

11:24.380 --> 11:25.960
Well, ma'am,
you know what?

11:25.960 --> 11:28.040
We take the complaints in the
order that they were received.

11:28.040 --> 11:29.580
Give me this.

11:29.580 --> 11:30.580
Oh, God, my book!

11:30.580 --> 11:32.080
Yes. Boom, we have solved
that problem.

11:32.080 --> 11:35.380
My complaint
is now number one.

11:35.380 --> 11:37.670
Okay, so why don't you
read that right now?

11:37.670 --> 11:38.960
Ma'am...
 Uh-huh?

11:38.960 --> 11:41.000
...you know,
if you just left the page in,

11:41.000 --> 11:42.580
your complaint would've been
heard eventually.

11:42.580 --> 11:43.880
Well, I want you
to hear me now.

11:43.880 --> 11:45.170
And do you hear me loud
and clear?

11:45.170 --> 11:46.710
Do you like wine?
 Oh, my God.

11:46.710 --> 11:48.380
I want you to know,
GirlStory,

11:48.380 --> 11:50.670
that you have made
a powerful enemy!

11:50.670 --> 11:52.540
I'm a doctor!
I save lives!

11:52.540 --> 11:54.540
♪♪

11:54.540 --> 11:56.120
Bye!

11:56.120 --> 11:58.000
Ace of clubs.

11:58.000 --> 12:00.710
Ooh.
Nice one, Zoey!

12:00.710 --> 12:02.290
Ruby: Oh, Junior.
Come on, now!

12:02.290 --> 12:04.210
There are no compliments
in Spades!

12:04.210 --> 12:05.920
You're terrible
at trash-talk!

12:05.920 --> 12:07.120
[ Grunts ]

12:07.120 --> 12:09.750
No, please don't give up
on me!

12:09.750 --> 12:11.000
I can be bad.

12:11.000 --> 12:12.170
Oh, my God.
Can you?

12:12.170 --> 12:13.460
Yeah.

12:13.460 --> 12:14.790
Oh.
 Oh.
 [ Chuckles ]

12:16.290 --> 12:18.960
Oh, no.
That's gonna bring ants.

12:18.960 --> 12:21.710
Ooh, we're gonna have
to practice more than I thought!

12:21.710 --> 12:23.120
But we're hungry!

12:23.120 --> 12:24.750
And we're supposed
to be at school today.

12:24.750 --> 12:26.790
Oh, you're at school.

12:26.790 --> 12:28.170
Ugh! [ Laughs ]

12:28.170 --> 12:28.960
Again!

12:28.960 --> 12:30.080
But my tummy...

12:30.080 --> 12:32.830
Again!
Come on!

12:32.830 --> 12:34.460
Dre: Bam!
There you have it.

12:34.460 --> 12:36.670
The new gold standard.

12:36.670 --> 12:38.330
Oh.
 Right?

12:38.330 --> 12:40.040
Stevens: Outstanding.
 Love it!

12:40.040 --> 12:41.380
Oh, h-hold up.

12:41.380 --> 12:43.170
Why are the DeBarges
the new face of Boxable?

12:43.170 --> 12:44.290
Charlie:
Oh, I'll tell you why.

12:44.290 --> 12:46.210
'Cause our boy Dre here's
colorstruck.

12:46.210 --> 12:47.580
He's got
that Beige Rage.

12:47.580 --> 12:49.250
I do not.
 What is that?

12:49.250 --> 12:50.670
It means he has
a clear preference

12:50.670 --> 12:52.500
of light skin
over dark skin.

12:52.500 --> 12:54.210
I've always seen it

12:54.210 --> 12:55.620
[voice breaking]
and it's always hurt.

12:55.620 --> 12:57.710
♪ You know I'm proud to be
black, y'all ♪

12:57.710 --> 12:59.170
♪ And that's a fact, y'all ♪

12:59.170 --> 13:00.540
♪ And if you try
to take what's mine ♪

13:00.540 --> 13:02.080
♪ I take it back, y'all ♪

13:02.080 --> 13:04.500
♪ The world's full of hate,
discrimination, and sin ♪

13:04.500 --> 13:07.250
♪ People judgin' other people
by the color of skin ♪

13:07.250 --> 13:08.710
♪ I'm fresh out the pack ♪

13:08.710 --> 13:10.250
♪ And I'm proud to be black ♪

13:10.250 --> 13:11.670
That was candy.

13:11.670 --> 13:14.710
And damn it, Charlie.
You always forget to dribble!

13:14.710 --> 13:15.920
This time,
this time, this time!

13:15.920 --> 13:17.120
Go!

13:17.120 --> 13:19.000
Kobe!
 What are you -- No!

13:19.830 --> 13:21.830
Maybe those wasn't
the best examples.

13:21.830 --> 13:23.500
Stevens:
Now that I think about it,

13:23.500 --> 13:25.830
let's take a look at
some of those past campaigns

13:25.830 --> 13:27.290
that you've run for us.

13:27.290 --> 13:29.710
Ooh. I wouldn't know
they were black.

13:29.710 --> 13:30.790
Gluten-free.
 Curtis: Yeah.

13:30.790 --> 13:32.960
Ooh.
That's milky right there.

13:32.960 --> 13:34.460
You know what?
Y'all sound ridiculous.

13:34.460 --> 13:36.460
All right,
I do not have a preference

13:36.460 --> 13:40.000
for light-skinned people,
as I am a dark-skinned man.

13:40.000 --> 13:42.210
[ Laughs ]
Wait, wait.

13:42.210 --> 13:44.120
So you think
you Team Dark Skin?
 What the hell
would you call it?

13:44.120 --> 13:45.500
Well, I personally think
you're --
 No, no, no!

13:45.500 --> 13:47.880
No, you got that kinda like --
 Stop it, stop it, stop it.

13:47.880 --> 13:49.670
I am not a colorist.

13:49.670 --> 13:51.750
Well, why don't you walk us
through your casting process?

13:51.750 --> 13:54.830
Fine. I did the exact same thing
I did with the first ad.

13:54.830 --> 13:56.830
I auditioned
a few black families,

13:56.830 --> 14:00.330
and I chose who I felt
was best to sell the image.

14:00.330 --> 14:02.210
So in order for me
to sell something,

14:02.210 --> 14:04.920
I have to have a keen nose,
green eyes...
 Curtis: Mm-hmm.

14:04.920 --> 14:08.000
...straight hair, paper lips,
and no ass.

14:08.000 --> 14:09.170
He's right, boss.

14:09.170 --> 14:10.330
The reason
you like this family

14:10.330 --> 14:11.920
is because they look closest
to white.

14:11.920 --> 14:13.500
No way.

14:13.500 --> 14:16.330
Lupita Nyong'o
 was on my free-pass list.

14:16.330 --> 14:18.420
I don't have a preference
 for light over dark.

14:18.420 --> 14:21.380
All right, so, we got
four black coffees,

14:21.380 --> 14:24.000
and one iced caramel macchiato
with extra cream.

14:24.000 --> 14:26.750
♪♪

14:26.750 --> 14:28.670
Oh.
 Oh, there it is.

14:28.670 --> 14:30.210
Stevens: That's interesting.
 That's just sad.

14:30.210 --> 14:31.620
Extra cream.
 [ Slurping ]

14:31.620 --> 14:33.620
It's the Michael Jackson
of coffee.

14:33.620 --> 14:35.420
[ Door closes ]

14:35.420 --> 14:36.420
What's going on
over there?

14:36.420 --> 14:39.540
Oh, Dre,
in every great movement,

14:39.540 --> 14:41.330
someone has to stand up

14:41.330 --> 14:43.750
and be a voice for those that
cannot speak for themselves.

14:43.750 --> 14:45.750
These dolls
can't speak, Dre.

14:45.750 --> 14:47.420
I speak for the dolls.

14:47.420 --> 14:49.380
"Shonda not slaves"?
 Yes.

14:49.380 --> 14:50.670
"Black Toys Matter"?

14:50.670 --> 14:52.040
Yeah.

14:52.040 --> 14:54.210
"Welcome to
Misty Nope-Land"?

14:54.210 --> 14:55.830
Yeah.

14:55.830 --> 14:59.040
It's hard being
a one-woman revolution, Dre.

14:59.040 --> 15:00.380
I'm spread
a little bit thin.

15:00.380 --> 15:02.040
Yeah, no,
I hear you, Bow.

15:02.040 --> 15:03.620
Change is hard.
 It's so hard.

15:03.620 --> 15:05.790
You know, I thought
I was gonna heal the world

15:05.790 --> 15:08.080
with positive images
of black people.

15:08.080 --> 15:10.210
Turns out,
I'm infected.

15:10.210 --> 15:13.000
What?
 I got that Beige Rage.

15:13.000 --> 15:15.330
Okay, I don't know what the hell
you're talking about, Dre,

15:15.330 --> 15:18.460
but instead of whining,
you need to take action

15:18.460 --> 15:21.080
against the injustices
that you see.

15:21.080 --> 15:24.080
You want a big change,
make a big move!

15:24.080 --> 15:25.540
Come on, Dre!

15:28.170 --> 15:30.540
Is that the guy
that is the captain now?

15:30.540 --> 15:32.210
No, that's Akon.

15:32.210 --> 15:34.380
This is a real miss,
Dre.

15:34.380 --> 15:36.670
You've jeopardized
the whole campaign.

15:36.670 --> 15:38.540
What the hell happened
to the DeBarges?

15:38.540 --> 15:40.960
Dre, this was supposed to be
your "Do the Right Thing,"

15:40.960 --> 15:43.250
but it is your
"Chi-Raq."
 Uhh!

15:43.250 --> 15:45.250
Well, clearly
 I'd blown my shot.

15:45.250 --> 15:47.880
I hoped Bow was having better
 luck with her revolution.

15:47.880 --> 15:50.040
Rainbow: Burn, dolls, burn!

15:50.040 --> 15:52.080
Burn, dolls, burn!

15:52.080 --> 15:53.960
Black toys matter!

15:53.960 --> 15:55.710
Sweetheart,
put the sign up.

15:55.710 --> 15:57.580
I really don't want to.
 Up, up, up, up
so they can see your face.

15:57.580 --> 16:00.330
No, my babies!
No! No!

16:00.330 --> 16:01.290
No! No!

16:01.290 --> 16:02.580
Yeah!

16:02.580 --> 16:04.710
Ooh, ooh. Oh, no!
 Oh, God.

16:04.710 --> 16:06.710
Ooh, ooh, ooh, ooh.
Oh, no!

16:06.710 --> 16:08.420
I-I don't have
any benefits!

16:08.420 --> 16:10.500
[ Screaming ]

16:14.170 --> 16:15.580
We're not gonna get
cinnamon rolls, are we?

16:15.580 --> 16:16.460
No rolls, no rolls!

16:20.750 --> 16:22.170
Junior, I hope you brought
your A-game,

16:22.170 --> 16:24.380
because that grand prize has got
my name written all over it!

16:24.380 --> 16:25.920
What's the grand prize?

16:25.920 --> 16:28.830
It's a $50 gift card
to Forever 21.

16:28.830 --> 16:31.330
Hello, Ruby.

16:31.330 --> 16:33.960
Doris.
 Girl,
look who she got

16:33.960 --> 16:35.920
to take Dead Earnest's
place.

16:35.920 --> 16:37.830
You know
she like young men.

16:37.830 --> 16:39.210
[ Laughs ]

16:39.210 --> 16:41.420
Come on, girl.
Let's go.

16:41.420 --> 16:43.330
I'm gonna kill her.

16:43.330 --> 16:44.920
Hello, grandmother.

16:44.920 --> 16:46.040
Hey,
what y'all doing here?

16:46.040 --> 16:47.670
Both: Vengeance.

16:47.670 --> 16:49.500
You think you can
just insult us,

16:49.500 --> 16:52.080
starve us,
flick lit cigarettes at us,

16:52.080 --> 16:53.750
and we just take that
lying down?

16:53.750 --> 16:55.210
Well...
 We must break you.

16:55.210 --> 16:56.620
We've been practicing.

16:56.620 --> 16:58.920
Let's do this,
old maid.

16:58.920 --> 17:00.290
[ Air horn blows ]

17:00.290 --> 17:02.210
♪ Try to be best,
'cause you're only a man ♪

17:02.210 --> 17:04.380
♪ And a man's got to learn
to take it ♪

17:04.380 --> 17:06.710
Boom! Roasted!

17:06.710 --> 17:09.540
We did it!
In your face!

17:09.540 --> 17:11.790
Oh.
 [ Chuckles ]

17:14.920 --> 17:16.000
We lost, didn't we?

17:16.000 --> 17:18.540
Badly.

17:18.540 --> 17:20.540
Next?
 ♪ Try to be best,
'cause you're only a man ♪

17:20.540 --> 17:22.210
♪ And a man's got to learn
to take it ♪

17:22.210 --> 17:26.000
Aww, Myrtle.
Only two books?

17:26.000 --> 17:29.000
Good news is, you won't remember
any of this tomorrow!

17:29.000 --> 17:31.210
[ Laughs ]
That's how you do it!

17:31.210 --> 17:33.250
[ Both laugh ]

17:33.250 --> 17:36.710
Hello!
 ♪ You're the best around ♪

17:36.710 --> 17:38.670
Gloria.
Guess what.

17:38.670 --> 17:40.880
Cheryl slept
with your husband.

17:40.880 --> 17:43.710
[ Laughs ] Hell, girl.
I'm just lyin'.

17:43.710 --> 17:46.170
Rodney did.
Yeah, ain't that right, Rodney?

17:46.170 --> 17:49.380
♪ Never stop,
You can't give up ♪

17:49.380 --> 17:51.960
♪ Until you reach the top ♪

17:51.960 --> 17:53.920
Well, well, Ruby.

17:53.920 --> 17:57.460
We both bid at seven,
but only one of us

17:57.460 --> 17:59.290
is walking away
with the means

17:59.290 --> 18:03.210
to purchase
a crop top denim vest.

18:03.210 --> 18:06.500
You can't wear
a crop top denim vest, Doris.

18:06.500 --> 18:08.040
Who gonna stop me?

18:08.040 --> 18:09.210
Oh.

18:09.210 --> 18:11.880
[ Laughs ]

18:11.880 --> 18:13.420
Well, I guess
I'm gonna see you

18:13.420 --> 18:16.750
in that crop top
denim vest

18:16.750 --> 18:19.790
in...hell!

18:19.790 --> 18:22.500
♪ You're the best around ♪
 Oh, you cheated!

18:22.500 --> 18:24.580
♪ Nothing's gonna ever
keep you down ♪

18:24.580 --> 18:27.290
♪ You're the best around ♪

18:27.290 --> 18:29.540
♪ Nothing's gonna ever
keep you down ♪

18:29.540 --> 18:31.710
Thank you very much.

18:31.710 --> 18:33.330
Well, just got off the phone
with the lawyer.

18:33.330 --> 18:35.330
Fortunately for you,
they're not gonna press charges.

18:35.330 --> 18:37.210
Oh, thank God.
 But there are
some stipulations.

18:37.210 --> 18:39.830
You're not allowed
near that mall...
 What?

18:39.830 --> 18:42.040
...or any GirlStory
franchise,

18:42.040 --> 18:45.580
or within 500 feet
of someone named Patrice.

18:45.580 --> 18:46.500
"Pat-riss."

18:46.500 --> 18:48.790
I set her on fire.

18:48.790 --> 18:50.540
What?
 She doesn't have benefits.

18:50.540 --> 18:54.500
Well, I put the entire cast
of "Captain Phillips"

18:54.500 --> 18:56.620
in a shipping commercial.

18:56.620 --> 18:57.460
Did not go over
too well.

18:57.460 --> 18:58.750
Hmm.

18:58.750 --> 19:00.710
Bow, why did you
encourage me

19:00.710 --> 19:02.380
to make change
in the world?

19:02.380 --> 19:04.460
Why didn't you stop me from
making change in the world, Dre?

19:04.460 --> 19:06.080
You saw my signs.

19:06.080 --> 19:09.120
You know what? We are no good
when we're on the same page.

19:09.120 --> 19:11.830
One of us needs to be clipping
the other's wings.

19:11.830 --> 19:14.290
Dre, when you walk
into that store,

19:14.290 --> 19:17.080
the messages
are so clear.

19:17.080 --> 19:18.120
There's something better.

19:18.120 --> 19:20.670
We're not as good.
 Mm.

19:20.670 --> 19:23.790
I just really didn't want Diane
internalizing that message.

19:23.790 --> 19:26.670
Yeah. I also did what I did
for Diane.

19:27.790 --> 19:29.080
Sometimes it just --
it feels like

19:29.080 --> 19:30.710
no matter how much progress
we make,

19:30.710 --> 19:33.580
it's one step forward
and two steps back.

19:33.580 --> 19:35.380
Why bother?

19:35.380 --> 19:37.750
Hey, you show me
one revolutionary

19:37.750 --> 19:40.880
who gave up their fight
because of one minor setback.

19:40.880 --> 19:42.380
You're right.

19:42.380 --> 19:44.670
Hey, come here.

19:45.750 --> 19:47.580
[ Sighing ]
Oh, man.

19:47.580 --> 19:49.210
Until the world
catches up,

19:49.210 --> 19:51.920
we're just gonna have to keep
reinforcing the messages

19:51.920 --> 19:54.250
that we want our kids
to hear at home.

19:54.250 --> 19:55.500
Yeah.
 But not you.

19:55.500 --> 19:57.290
You're not
a good role model.

19:57.290 --> 19:58.420
[ Chuckles ] Oh, God.

19:58.420 --> 20:00.210
You set a lady on fire,
Bow.

20:00.210 --> 20:01.290
I didn't mean to.

20:01.290 --> 20:03.620
[ Both chuckle ]

20:07.880 --> 20:09.120
Hey, sweetie.
 Hi.

20:09.120 --> 20:11.620
So, I wanted to talk to you
about how I acted today.

20:11.620 --> 20:14.420
Yeah.
That was so cool.

20:14.420 --> 20:16.330
I've never seen fire spread
so fast.

20:16.330 --> 20:18.040
I used an accelerant.
 Whoa!

20:18.040 --> 20:20.710
No, that -- that is not the
point. That's not the point.

20:20.710 --> 20:21.830
Here.

20:21.830 --> 20:23.080
Come here, sweetie.

20:23.080 --> 20:25.830
I just wanted to say
I'm sorry.

20:25.830 --> 20:27.420
I didn't set
a very good example today,

20:27.420 --> 20:30.080
and, you know,
I want you to know

20:30.080 --> 20:32.830
that just because
that doll store

20:32.830 --> 20:34.920
thinks that
we're only one thing,

20:34.920 --> 20:37.040
that doesn't mean
that's all we are.

20:37.040 --> 20:41.580
Mom, I don't need some doll
to tell me that.

20:41.580 --> 20:45.460
I have you.
And you're a doctor.

20:45.460 --> 20:47.330
And you're constantly
reminding us of that.

20:47.330 --> 20:50.500
I am constantly reminding you
of that, Diane,

20:50.500 --> 20:52.210
because I want you to know

20:52.210 --> 20:54.960
that you can be
anything you want to be.

20:54.960 --> 20:58.500
So in that spirit --
here.

20:58.500 --> 21:00.040
[ Chuckles ]
 Okay?

21:00.040 --> 21:02.120
Go for it.

21:02.120 --> 21:04.000
[ Chuckles ]
 Okay.

21:04.000 --> 21:05.540
[ Laughs ]

21:05.540 --> 21:07.420
Nunchucks!
Thank you!

21:07.420 --> 21:08.460
Oh,
and don't worry, Mom.

21:08.460 --> 21:09.880
It is my solemn promise

21:09.880 --> 21:11.380
that I will never
use these on you.

21:11.380 --> 21:12.620
Or anyone
in the house.

21:15.290 --> 21:17.000
No -- No, I'm serious.

21:17.000 --> 21:18.500
Thank you very much.
